<Base title="The Science Simplified">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>The Science (Simplified)</h1>

    <p>
      You don't need a neuroscience degree to understand what's happening in your nervous system. 
      Here's how chronic pain gets stuck — and how it can get unstuck.
    </p>

    <h2>Normal pain: the alarm system</h2>
    <p>
      Imagine your body has a fire alarm. You touch a hot stove → nerves detect danger → they 
      send a signal up your spinal cord to your brain → your brain says "Ouch!" and you pull away. 
      The alarm turns off when the danger is gone.
    </p>

    <h2>Neuroplastic pain: the stuck alarm</h2>
    <p>
      With chronic pain, something goes wrong with the alarm system itself. The wiring changes. 
      Your spinal cord and brain become <strong>sensitized</strong> — they've learned to amplify 
      pain signals. Now even a light breeze feels like a fire. The alarm keeps ringing even though 
      there's no fire.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-weight: 600;">Key concept: Central Sensitization</p>
      <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        "Central" = your central nervous system (brain + spinal cord). "Sensitization" = it's become 
        too reactive. Your nervous system is generating pain in response to things that aren't 
        actually dangerous.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>What changes in your brain?</h2>
    <p>Researchers have identified several changes:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pain pathways get stronger</strong> — the neural connections involved in pain become more efficient, like a well-worn trail through a forest</li>
      <li><strong>Pain inhibition weakens</strong> — your brain's natural pain-killing systems stop working as well</li>
      <li><strong>Emotion centers get involved</strong> — fear, anxiety, and vigilance circuits connect to pain circuits, so stress directly worsens pain</li>
      <li><strong>Body maps distort</strong> — the brain regions that represent your body can send confused signals</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How does the brain learn pain?</h2>
    <p>
      The same <strong>neuroplasticity</strong> that lets you learn a new language or ride a bike also 
      lets your brain learn pain patterns. When pain persists for weeks, your brain adapts to produce 
      pain more efficiently. This was once protective — keeping you careful while injured — but it 
      becomes a trap when it outlasts the injury.
    </p>

    <h2>The hopeful part</h2>
    <p>
      Here's the key insight: <strong>neuroplasticity works both ways.</strong> The same brain 
      flexibility that learned pain can learn safety. This is the foundation of treatments like 
      Pain Reprocessing Therapy and Pain Neuroscience Education — they retrain your brain to 
      recognize that the danger signal is a false alarm.
    </p>

    <p>
      A landmark 2022 study (Ashar et al., JAMA Psychiatry) showed that 66% of chronic back pain 
      patients became pain-free after 4 weeks of PRT. Simply learning how pain works has measurable 
      therapeutic effects — a phenomenon called Pain Neuroscience Education.
    </p>

